Text: South of here lies the ruin known as the Mortal Irons, erstwhile home to the wardens of the Hour of Certain Durance. Tales say it was once known by a less somber name. Either way, I get the chills just thinking about it.

Travel north along this path and you'll reach the ruin known as the Stay. It was once a proud fort built by the elves in the days when they still ruled, to defend Lakeland from an invasion by the Kingdom of Voeburt.
Lali-ho! Following the road here will take you towards Komra...and those sulphur-licking Goggs. Honestly, I'm not sure why we even bothered to make this path...
Lali-hooo! Welcome to Tomra, home of the Tholls! Behave yourself in town, or we'll strap you down and leave you for the knockers. Have a nice day!
Lali-ho! There ain't much north of Tomra but Mt. Gulg itself. And I don't advise you to go up there without a full team of miners at your back...
The good thing about guarding this place is that the desert creatures take care of most would-be bandits. That just leaves the beasts themselves...
Are you heading to Mord Souq? It's that place with the big tower on the other side of the ravine. And watch out for the gigantenders!
If you're crossing the desert, try to stick close to the rocky outcrops. There are all sorts of nasty things lurking beneath the sand...
We're surrounded by remnants of the old Nabaath Empire. Some even say the ghilman are the wandering souls of their dead. You know, I've always felt this is no place for the living...
I know they're up to something. I <Italic>1</Italic>know<Italic>0</Italic> it. But I cannot simply leave the periphery unobserved while I go and get a closer look!
In order to undertake the quest “Fear and Delight,” you must first complete the quest “It's Probably Pirates.”
What do the fiends <Italic>1</Italic>want<Italic>0</Italic>? What keeps them coming back year after year? I need to know...
What can we do for you this fine All Saints' Wake? Are you here for chills? Thrills? Cookies? We <Italic>1</Italic>do<Italic>0</Italic> have cookies.
I can hardly wait to see how dreadful the ahriman's gaze has become by next year's All Saints' Wake! Ah, it sends shivers down my spine just to think of it!
Well, I certainly hope that you two are happy together. Hmph.
Hello there, darling! I hope you're having a properly frightful time! If you're not, well─let me know. I'm sure that I can fix that right up!
I'm sorry <If(PlayerParameter(4))>madam<Else/>sir</If>, but we can fit not a single additional morta─er, guest in the mansion at the moment.
Folks ought to keep busy, that's my motto. Idle hands are the fae's playthings.
Wicked white, if you start pestering me like those twins to get inside... \\<sigh> I tell you, what's the point of being a guard if you can't profit off it? Why would anyone ever take this job?
What kind of things could one find in a machine graveyard, anyway...? Gah, I have to know! Maybe I'll sneak into Komra my very own self...
\\<squeal> \\<squeal>
It seems to be saying, “Give me milk.”
\\<squeal> \\<squeal>
It seems to be saying, “The marble is pretty. Thank you.”
\\<squeal> \\<squeal> \\<squeal>
It seems to be saying, “I found my friends. Thank you.”
Yes, yeees... Our plans for world domination are proceeding apace...
Heh heh heh... And should anyone attempt to interfere, we will attend to them with great prejudice, heh heh heh...
We had always hoped the allies of Ronka would someday come, that our duty to the emperor might be fulfilled. Now that you are here, I am honestly not sure what to think.
The Eulmorans will pay dearly for what they have done.
It was foretold that one day you would come to our village, but never did we imagine your coming would return the night sky to us. We are forever in your debt.
I... I do not understand. Why has the Light returned? Was what we saw before a trick of the sin eaters?
So this is the sky as it was before the Flood? The sun, moon, and stars are all quite beautiful. I pray the Light does not return to obscure them from our sight.
Do you feel that? The breeze blows toward the Morning Stars. A good omen. After a long day on patrol, sleep comes easy knowing the gods smile upon us.
The Eulmoran soldiers are unlike anything I have ever seen. Their leader especially. To outpace even our swiftest hunters... He is not to be taken lightly.
Have you seen the sky? I know not how, but the Light is gone! For the first time since the Flood, we can all enjoy a good night's rest.
To think the sky was so beautiful such a short time ago...
I had always wondered what it would be like to sleep under the gentle light of a full moon. I cannot say I have ever slept so soundly.
You retrieved the seal of Ronka from the Covered Halls of Dwatl, is that right? I am told it was quite beautiful in the days of the empire. Would that I could see it for myself.
Had the Eulmorans not retreated, I would have gladly put each and every one to the sword.
On occasion the texts of Ronkan history would mention the night sky. But I see now that words do little to capture its splendor.
The texts of the ancients of foretold much of what has and will happen, but nothing of these recent changes in the sky. Perhaps I overlooked something.
Fanow has changed much since your arrival. Perhaps one day I will be permitted to leave and visit the ruins of the Citia Swamps.
Your coming was foretold long ago, and yet still we were unprepared for your arrival. Judging by your dress, the world beyond the Greatwood has seen much change. Much change indeed.
That the Eulmorans would not only trespass in these woods, but infiltrate our temples... It is a shame we will carry for many, many years. I pray we may someday make amends for this disgrace.
You found a Lightwarden beyond the Qitana Ravel? It chose its nest well, for no one─not even we, its protectors─would ever step foot there.
Our life here in the Greatwood has remained unchanging for so long, it is strange to see so much happen so quickly. I can but wonder if we will be able to keep up.
It seems we are at last entering an age of peace. Nevertheless, we must remain vigilant in guarding the ruins. The knowledge within must not fall into the wrong hands.
No doubt you have noticed the winding trails of azure flowers throughout the woods. We call them the Steps of Maja, for it was along those paths Her footfalls gave rise to the flowers you see today.
It is said one will receive Her protection by walking along those paths. And to that end I bid you walk in the Steps of Maja, ally of Ronka, and may Her blessings be upon you.

It was not until the blazing skies above dissipated that I realized the true beauty of the Steps of Maja. Watch the flowers at night, and you will see them glow with Her blessing. It is how She helps guide us in the dark.
Be welcome, ally of Ronka. If there is anything you would ask of us, do not hesitate to ask.

The ravine above which our village was built is called the Ox'Dalan Gap, so named in reverence to the god of death. As you might surmise from its name, none who have fallen into its depths has survived. So do be careful.
Seeing how much Phyna and Ciuna have grown, I am quite confident our future will be in good hands.
Establishing open relations with Slitherbough will require significant change for my people, but ultimately I believe it will be for the better good.
The night sky is so beautiful. It has been so long since I last beheld it, I had nearly forgotten...
I still remember that fateful day when Light claimed the sky. I never thought I would live to endure such misery twice...
When the younglings asked me to describe the night sky, I had always been at a loss for words. But now, thanks to you, they need only gaze up at the heavens.

Though often uneventful, patrol of the ruins can be exhausting. And worse, I have yet to eat today.
I should have hunted a stag before I returned...
With darkness returned to the world, and our duty to the emperor fulfilled, perhaps we can afford to be less stringent in our patrols. I think we all could do with a short rest.

My apologies for our informal welcome. It was a dream of mine to prepare a feast for the allies of Ronka should they one day arrive to our village. But your arrival was so unexpected, I had no time to prepare.
Your defeat of the Lightwarden is what returned the night to us, is it not? We should feast to celebrate! Oh, but what should I prepare for such a momentous occasion? Hmmm...
The Light has returned, and we have yet to even celebrate its retreat. What am I to do with all this food now?
The Night's Blessed have told me of all manner of wonderful foods found beyond the Greatwood. What I would not give to try them.
We live a good life here in Fanow. A simple life. So long as we keep watch of the ruins, the woods will provide for us.
There is talk of trade with the Night's Blessed. Perhaps even the Crystarium. These are strange times for Fanow. But also quite interesting.
After a long day on patrol, it is not uncommon for those on duty to stop at Bowrest. The tents and provisions are sufficient to rest before returning to Fanow.
Bowrest is meant to be a place to repose after patrol, but recently we have been gathering there to simply gaze up at the stars.
People from all walks of life are welcome among the Night's Blessed. Our faith in the Dark is infinitely greater than the sum of our differences.
The soldiers ruined our crops when they trampled through the village. I pray our emergency stores will last until we can grow more.
It should go without saying we were overjoyed to see the return of the night sky, but I did not stop to consider the bounty of the sun. Our gardens have never looked better.
Though the Light has returned, we will not be discouraged. Darkness <Italic>1</Italic>will<Italic>0</Italic> prevail.
Nothing gives me greater joy than to sit down for dinner with my fellow Blessed under a starry sky. Truly we are blessed in every sense of the word.
All are welcome here at Slitherbough, though there have been few if any newcomers since the attack on Fort Gohn.
Time and again we have refused the overtures of Eulmore, but now that the Children have joined them... This bodes ill for the Greatwood.
The night sky is more breathtaking than I dared imagine. Would that Toddia were here to see it, but I take comfort in knowing she smiles down upon us from the sunless sea.
The Light's return is a test of our faith, but we shall not be broken.
Our faith in the Dark has been rewarded, and balance has at last been struck with the Light. I very much look forward to seeing what the future holds for our people.
Have you heard? The Warrior of Darkness has returned night to Lakeland and Il Mheg! I imagine it won't be long before the prayers of the Greatwood are answered as well.
All my life I have prayed for the night's return, but I never thought I would live to see it.
I fear some ill fate has befallen the Warrior of Darkness. What else could explain the Light's return?
Praise be to the Warrior of Darkness! The night sky has returned, no doubt by their doing.
I realize they are not a god to be worshipped, but such selflessness is deserving of veneration.
I still remember when I first came here as a child. Everyone was still dressed in garbs of all sorts and colors. We'd yet to find any sense of community back then.
My sight is too far gone to see the stars, but I can feel it─the cool air, the tender touch of the moonlight. It calls to mind the bedtime stories my parents would tell me.
The air has grown foul with the Light's presence again. I do not like it. No, not at all...
The quiet of Slitherbough has given way to the sounds of joy and excitement. Especially the children. Each night they tell me what they can see, and in turn I try to teach them of constellations.
Compared to the guardians of Yx'Maja, we are but children newly come to the Greatwood. But they leave us be, so long as we keep away from their territory.
We have always maintained a rather uneasy coexistence with the Children, but with the weight of Eulmore now behind them, I fear for the Greatwood.

I am as happy as any of the Night's Blessed to see the return of the Dark, but we mustn't grow complacent. The night is not without its dangers, and the Children would not hesitate to take advantage of our indolence.

In the short time we were able to enjoy the night sky, I learned much of how our defenses were lacking. I have faith the Dark will return. And when it does, our guard shall be duly prepared to keep Slitherbough safe.

There has been an influx of volunteers for the night guard. There is no doubt in my mind that many of them only seek an excuse to gaze up at the stars... But if it fills our ranks, I suppose I can allow it.

A great many of the plants near Slitherbough can be used to make dye. Though but tatters of their former glory, the purple standards surrounding the village's entrance are a testament to the abundance of materials at our disposal.
With the threat of sin eaters largely gone, we may resume the rebuilding of Fort Gohn in earnest. I certainly hope you will be here to see it.
We use these jugs to produce yeast. Of all the goods we have to trade, it is perhaps the most valuable.
The roads are much safer than they used to be, meaning trade has increased substantially. We can scarcely keep up with the demand for our yeast.

We may appear secluded here in the Greatwood, but we do, on occasion, trade with the Crystarium and Mord Souq. Dyed goods for pottery, yeast for meats and other foodstuffs. Only what we find absolutely necessary.
The threat of sin eaters is not what it once was, meaning more traders traveling to Slitherbough. We are a simple people, but I cannot help but wonder how this might affect us.
The unchanging sky makes it difficult to judge the passing of time. That is why it's so important to have our meals at the same time each day, to help our bodies maintain their natural rhythm.
I cannot believe Eulmore would willingly aid those zealots of Woven Oath. What are we to do when they return?
Looking up at the sky, it feels as though time has taken its first steps forward since the Flood.
The stagnant sky returns to torment us, but we mustn't lose hope. The Warrior of Darkness will set things right.

When I was a girl, my great-grandmother would tell me stories of a time before the Flood. They always ended with a setting sun, and the hero living happily ever after. Finally it's our turn to have a happy ending.
My brother and I came here two years ago after the great fire. It still hurts to think of home, and all that we've lost.
I never realized how much I detest the Light until the skies turned that horrible shade of primordial white. When I see it I can only think of the sin eaters that attacked our home.

There's a renewed interest in rebuilding Fort Gohn. In fact, some of the Night's Blessed have left to the Crystarium to train and become craftsman. I could never do anything so adventurous as that, but mark my words: I will find a way to help.
Was it fate that brought you to usss...?
Chosen of the ancient ones... Were you welcomed into the illuminated land?
The ancients have blessed us with protection and prosperity. If your presence ssserves to bring us the sssame, there will be no doubt in the matter.
You <Italic>1</Italic>are<Italic>0</Italic> the chosen of the ancients. I knew it to be so...
You are a visitor to the Crystarium? Feel free to wander the Rookery, but keep an eye on the amaro─some of them bite.
How fared you in Kholusia? Have you grown accustomed to our amaro mounts?
You know our oceans now, yes? Do you not find it apt that the night sky has ever been known as the sunless sea?

You seem much preoccupied, <split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>. I appreciate the deeds you do for the city, but one who tires <If(PlayerParameter(4))>her<Else/>his</If> wings overmuch risks falling from the sky.
Blessed shadow keep us!
We witnessed your bravery, <split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>. Full many citizens are alive now thanks to your swift actions. You have our gratitude.
It is good to see you returned to us. You are recovered from your injuries, then...?
I pray you find the Exarch. We owe him everything─the Crystarium would not exist without his boundless compassion.
My fellow tamers and I will keep an eye on the horizon. Should the need arise, we shall speed to your side with a flock of amaro in tow.
You have brought back the night itself, and still you flutter to and fro. The Exarch, at least, seems amused to see you thus engaged.
I'm fine... I can still─ I'm fine...
<split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>! When did you come back to the First? I trust Tataru and the others are well?
For myself, I decided to stay here for a time, and have been doing what I can to help Eulmore adjust in the aftermath of Vauthry's tyranny.
...And in the spare moments I've had, I managed to finish that painting for Lord and Lady Chai. Considering all they have done, and all that lies ahead, it seemed a suitable gesture.
<split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>!? No one told me you were back!
Well, never mind that. You should try speaking with Halric!
I've come to believe that some miracles simply require an inordinate amount of stubbornness. That goes for your case, for Halric's...and I'm hoping for Ga Bu's as well!
There you are. I take it there were no pressing matters to keep you in the Source, then?
If not, I may have need of you in the near future. There is still yet so much to be learned of this world. So many mysteries begging to be solved.
The greatest perhaps being the truth of Emet-Selch's words that fateful day in the Qitana Ravel. A most troubling matter to be sure, but remember: it is not a burden you must bear alone.
Hm? If you've come looking for work, I might have a spot for another guard.
Ah, it's good to be back. Mord Souq has many charms, but there's nothing like a proper bed to recover from a long journey...as I'm sure you'd agree.
The return of night's wreaked havoc on demand, and as it turns out, it can be dangerous to travel in the dark. It'll take some getting used to...but that beautiful, starry sky is worth it.
They say the Eulmoran Army's headed for the Crystarium. This can't end well...
Sin eaters are coming! A whole bloody horde of them! I'm no warrior, but I'll help any way I can─even if that means carrying arrows to the front lines!
I saw you, <split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>─saw you fighting the eaters on the front lines. That was impressive stuff.
<split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>!? I thought you were bedridden!
While we're on the subject, I'm concerned for that Alisaie of yours. I'd thought her face stormy on that ride back from Amh Araeng, but now...it's closer to a raging tempest.
I might offer some words of encouragement to the masses while I'm out and about on business. You need proper support to do what you need to do, and we can't let morale start flagging now, can we?
<split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>, good to see you well. Of late, I can't help but remember our trip to the desert together. Feels like only yesterday, it does...
Yes, sweetie? Does something hurt?
The night is lovely and all, but do watch your step in the dark, yes? Why, not a moment ago I had to apply some very <Italic>1</Italic>bracing<Italic>0</Italic> ointment on a skinned knee.
Oh? You liked the taste so much, you want some more, is that it? Hee hee, you are a strange one!
Oh dear, we've never seen so many sin eaters before... We must make ready to receive the wounded.
Don't worry about the wounded, sweetie. We'll make sure they do not want for care.
Oh, sweetie! You had us all so worried!
I wish I could brew you a tonic, sweetie, but I've no idea how it might affect you...
...No, it's too dangerous. In the end, I can but pray for your well-being. May blessed shadow keep you, your friends, and the Exarch as well.
Hm? Do you need a tonic for your travels, sweetie? Oh, and maybe you should take one for the Exarch as well. Invigorating stuff if you can abide the smell...

Oh, sweetie, it's good to see you hale and whole! Whenever you're under the weather, don't hesitate to come here, yes? I'm sure we can find a tonic to perk you right up. No promises as to the taste, though. Hee hee!
\\<squeal> \\<squeal>
It seems to be saying, “I love milk. Thank you.”
I'm always pleased to welcome a new arrival. When the population swells, more goods start moving, and more trade means more growth...
Standing here, in the middle of the markets, I can feel the joy that's taken root in the city. Smiling faces everywhere I look─that's what I like to see.
Eulmore's dispatched its military, has it? I'll see that we won't be stuck for supplies. Better to be ready for the worst, than be caught unprepared.
Being in Eulmore's bad books has slowed things down for the markets...but that's for me to worry about. The best thing you can do is go about your business as usual.
If you're going into battle against that swarm of eaters, I suggest you stock up on potions and the like. And if you've any holes in your boots, now's the time to get them repaired!
Medical supplies are selling as soon as we stock them, but the shelves are still heavy with foodstuffs and clothing. So many who won't be coming home...
We'll need to invite the Eulmorans back to the bargaining table... Just a shame that it took something like this to bring them to their senses.
You still look a little worse for wear, my friend. If you can't stay abed, you should at least find yourself a nice, hot cup of tea or something...
All stocked up on supplies then? Better to have it and not need it, than need it and not have it, as my old man used to say. Be safe, and bring the Exarch back to us...

The question I hear most in the markets these days is, “What does the Warrior of Darkness buy?” Everyone wants to emulate their hero, right down to <If(PlayerParameter(4))>her<Else/>his</If> shopping list.
Not that our shopkeeps ever give them a straight answer, of course. We don't betray the privacy of our valued customers, let alone our dear friends.
I've been keeping that device you uncovered safe and sound. Did you need to use it again...?
The portal that brought you here has not yet closed. Were you to reach out and touch it, you would most likely be returned to the Source.
Do you wish to fly to Kholusia? Stormy skies or ocean gales, my hand-raised amaro soar swift and true!
Do you have business with the Crystal Exarch? Just say the word, and I would be happy to escort you to the Ocular.
Bound for Amh Araeng, are you? I can ready an amaro that knows its way around the desert currents.
You wish to ascend to the Canopy? Why, yes, this lift will take you there.
You wish to descend to the Buttress? I'll call the lift for you, then.
Any time you need it, the Ladder is at your service. Heading up to Top Rung, then?
It is now my proud duty to serve as a Ladder operator. If you wish to descend, I'll tell the lads down below to get those gears turning!
Back to the ocean floor, is it? ...Oh no, I'll just be rowin' you out into the bay. When it comes to gettin' down to the bottom, you're on your own, mate!
Flying back to the Crystarium, <If(PlayerParameter(4))>miss<Else/>sir</If>? It's perfectly safe─our amaro are swift and strong enough to escape any stray eater.
Your first order of business will be to reunite with Alphinaud and Alisaie. In so doing, the predicament here in Norvrandt should become abundantly clear.
As for communications with the Source, Feo Ul will gladly serve as your messenger. If needs be, however, you yourself should be capable of making the journey between worlds.
The device there will serve as a portal─simply touching a hand to its surface will transport you to the location of the beacon I left at the base of the tower. In theory, at least...
Back so soon, my friend? In case you were worried about us, do not be. All is well here.
On the contrary, I worry about you. The faeries are a mercurial folk who possess their own customs, far departed from those of men.
So pray focus on the task at hand, and nothing else. Rest assured that the Crystarium will still be standing upon your return.
I still remember the day my misguided attempts to summon you here drew Thancred to the First. When the realization of where he was dawned on him, the very first words from his mouth were of Minfilia.
'Tis not my place to speak of his struggles, but I pray that─when this is all over─he finds what he was looking for here in the First.

My informants have kept me abreast of the situation in Eulmore, and it does not bode well for us, I'm afraid. If you should have need of reinforcements, rest assured they shall be sent with all haste.

So long as we are in their realm, we must expect to be subjected to the faeries' mischief. Indeed, Minfilia and I have experienced more than our fair share of it. From the harmless to the downright murderous, we've seen it all.
Reasons notwithstanding, to live here for as long as Urianger has requires no small amount of forbearance. In that regard, he is a better man than I.
If the pixies offer to take you somewhere, take them up on it at your peril.
...That's the very first thing Urianger taught me.
I was asked to retrieve a garland from a tree branch. “The wind blew it there,” the pixie claimed. Questionable premise aside, the dragoon's jump would have been useful for this task...
So, I'm supposed to bring them a plank of wood. That has no wood grain. Hah hah hah...
You found Alisaie, then? I would've loved to have seen her reaction... Ah, but had I been there, she would've put on her <Italic>1</Italic>stoic<Italic>0</Italic> face!
<split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>...? I thought you were out with Alisaie?
Whenever I come to the Crystarium, the sands of Amh Araeng seem a world away. And yet they both lie under this same, wretched sky...
I will do what I can to decipher the tablet's contents as quickly as I can. Though I fear it will require time we can ill afford, even with Urianger's help.
In my time here, I read through texts covering all manner of topics regarding the Ronkan Empire, but there was surprisingly very little pertaining to linguistics.
I suspect they were lost in the chaos that ensued at the time of the Flood. If there were a word to describe such a terrible loss of knowledge, it is one we will now never know.
When Y'shtola first arrived in the First, she made swift work of the Cabinet of Curiosity. Her thirst yet unsated, she then journeyed hither seeking the wisdom of Ronka.
She found little in the way of welcome from the Blessed, however. 'Twas not until the great fire, where she denied the sin eaters a feast of aether, that she gained their trust.
Since then I have served as liaison 'twixt Slitherbough and the Crystarium, that she might be kept abreast of the others' efforts.
Proceed to Woven Oath with caution, I prithee. Should the Children find thee, they will not suffer thee to leave.
Do not be reckless. We would be glad to have her heartstone returned to us, but it is not worth both of your lives.
I had no right to involve you in our troubles. Still, without your help, today's service would not have been possible. The Night's Blessed are in your debt.
I realize there is no stopping you, so do what you must, and the Night's Blessed shall do the same.
I only ask that you keep Master Matoya safe. There is no denying she is powerful, but the path she needs is plain. Where she goes, she will have need of powerful allies.
You are returned! Where are Master Matoya and the others?
Master Matoya was only with us for two years, but she will remain in our hearts for a lifetime.
Safe travels, my friend. We will keep you all in our prayers.

<split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>! It is a relief to see you up and about, my friend. When Master Matoya came and told us what happened... I have never seen her so stricken with grief. We feared for the worst.
All things considered, we have done quite well since you were last here, but I fear your concern is misplaced. Such an ordeal has surely taken its toll on you. Please, go and rest.
Ah, the mighty hero returns to grace Slitherbough with <If(PlayerParameter(4))>her<Else/>his</If> presence. When the night sky returned, we knew at once that all would be right with the world.
Any doubts we may have had were quickly put to rest when Master Matoya came. It did my heart good to see her in such high spirits.
We should hold a feast to celebrate your victory. Then you can finally sample my famous stew!
<split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>. What brings an ally of Ronka to Fanow?
If there is aught you need, but ask and the Viis will answer.
We recently received one of your comrades, who made a most unusual request. They asked of a magic that could alter one's “elemental affinity.”
They scoured the ruins and pored over every tome we could find. Alas... Before they left, we also provided them with drawings of the Qitana Ravel's murals. I pray they might be of use to you.
Welcome, ally of Ronka. Your companion Y'shtola was here not long ago. It would seem the mural drawing was of use. She came to thank us, but it is we who must thank you.
We but did our duty to the allies of Ronka, and by your deeds the world has been returned to balance. On behalf of all of Fanow, I thank you.
Ah, <split(<String>ObjectParameter(1)</String>, ,1)>. It is good to see you again so soon.
Since your arrival, many of the Viis have grown curious of the outside world. Myself included. Should you be so inclined, we would all very much like to hear of your travels.
Though we did not foresee the return of the blazing skies, your arrival has taught us to expect the unexpected.
The woods have been blissfully quiet of late. I should think all of Norvrandt now enjoys such calm.
It is strange yet somehow exciting to think what will now become of us. Of the world.

You come from the Crystarium, yes? I recently met─or rather, apprehended─a merchant of that city. I had him in my sights, and had every intention of shooting. Yet something compelled me to instead speak with him.
He told me of a place with many different peoples, of a glittering tower that reaches to the heavens. It sounds like a wonderful place.
Has something happened? Aside from the return of the blazing sky, I mean.
Your companion Y'shtola came to us recently, terribly distraught. It shames me to think we were unable to help her.
Quiet and calm have returned to the Greatwood, and it has given me time to think of the future.
The empire of Ronka was vast, and remnants of its greatness reach far beyond the borders of Rak'tika. When the time is right, I wish to see them with my own eyes.
I prithee keep Thancred occupied in thy search for leonine.
Minfilia and I shall see to preparations for the Talos.
The Talos means the world to Magnus, despite what he might say. If you were able to find any leonine, it'd mean more to him than you know.
